info.name: VarSome QA Clinical API
info.description:
To use the api you need to request a token first via the support email.
In order to use the token to authenticate you need to pass an Authorization header with your request # noqa E501
with the value **Token your_token_here**. e.g.

```
import requests
headers = {
    'accept': "application/json",
    'accept-encoding': "gzip, deflate",
    'authorization': "Token your_token_here",
    }
url = "https://ch.clinical.varsome.com/api/v1/analysis/"
r = requests.post(url, data=payload, headers=headers)
print(r.json())
```

To access the Sample Files documentation (upload sample files, etc) please click
[here](/api/v1/docs/sample-files/).


Contact Support:
 Name: Support
 Email: support@varsome.com

request.description:
In case you want to batch start many analyses you can provide a list of the
required json properties
in the post body. e.g.
```javascript
 [{
     "subject_id": "string",
     "description": "string",
     "capture_kit_id": 0,
     "reference_genome": "hg19",
     "sample_file_ids": ...
  },
  {
     "subject_id": "string",
     "description": "string",
     "capture_kit_id": 0,
     "reference_genome": "hg19",
     "sample_file_ids": ...
 }]
```
You can use the assays endpoint to derive the capture kit identifier,
the phenotypes and diseases endpoint to derive the relevant phenotype_ids or
disease_ids
You can also start a gene list analysis for each of the analyses by either
providing a
+ genes property e.g. "genes": ["BRAF", "BRCA1"]
+ varsome_gene_list_ids property. One or more gene list ids fetched using the
Internal
gene lists endpoint
+ panelapp_gene_list_ids property. One or more gene list ids fetched using the
PanelApp
gene lists endpoint
+ gene_list_analysis_based_on_phenotypes property. By providing a list of
   phenotype_ids and the value **"all"** or **"any"**
   **all** means that the genes derived from the phenotypes would be the
   common ones in all phenotypes
   **any** means that the genes derived from the phenotypes are all
   taken into account

You may use a combination of the available options to launch the gene list
analysis by combining parameters including genes based on panelapp gene
lists, varsome gene lists, genes based on phenotypes, etc

request.description:
Starts a CNV analysis from FASTQ. You may start a CNV analysis from:

+ 5 or more (ideally, around 10) non-WGS germline or tumor samples, from the
       same sequencing run, as a cohort analysis. CNV calls on the X
       chromosome should only be trusted if the input samples are all the same sex.
       If a mix of male and female samples are used,
       CNV calls on the X chromosome will be unreliable.
+ 3 to 5 WGS samples, from the same sequencing run, as a cohort analysis.
        As above, CNV calls on the X chromosome should only be trusted if the
        input samples are all the same sex. If a mix of male and female
        samples are used,
        CNV calls on the X chromosome will be unreliable.
+ A single whole genome sample which will run as a single sample analysis.
+ 1 germline and 1 tumor whole genome samples, from the same individual
        and using the same assay, as a Tumor/Normal analysis.
        In order to start a CNV analysis from FASTQ:
+ The user must provide a list of integer analysis IDs.
+ The analyses must belong to the user/group and must be appropriate for CNV
            analyses starting from FASTQ.
+ According to the analysis type (germline, tumour, whole genome etc) a
            different order of analyses must be given. For a tumour-normal analysis
            the first analysis provided should be the tumour.
